eyears = 1986\u20131991<ref name=\"AUSA2011\"/>\n|rank         = [[File:US military captain's rank.gif|18px]] [[Captain (United States)|Captain]]<ref name=\"AUSA2011\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ausa.org/legislation/congressionalinfo/Documents/OAS%20112th%20Congress.pdf|title=Once a Soldier... Always a Soldier|author=Staff|year=2011|work=Legislative Agenda|publisher=[[Association of the United States Army]]|accessdate=January 26, 2013}}</ref>\n|unit         = [[7th Cavalry Regiment|2nd Squadron, 7th Cavalry Regiment]], [[4th Infantry Division (United States)|4th Infantry Division]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pompeo.house.gov/biography|title=Biography \u2013 Congressman Mike Pompeo|publisher=house.gov}}</ref>\n|website      = {{url|pompeo.house.gov|House website}}\n<!-- |footnotes    = {{small|<nowiki>*</nowiki>Pending Senate confirmation}} -->\n}}\n'''Michael Richard''' \"'''Mike'''\" '''Pompeo''' (born December 30, 1963) is an American politician who has been the [[United States House of Representatives|U.S. Representative]] for {{ushr|KS|4}} since 2011. He is a member of the [[Tea Party movement]] within the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Gehrke|first1=Joel|title=Tea-Party Power Endures|url=http://www.nationalreview.com/article/384793/tea-party-power-endures-joel-gehrke|accessdate=29 December 2016|publisher=National Review|date=August 7, 2014}}</ref><ref>[http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2014/08/06/kansas-gop-sen-roberts-survives-tea-party-backed-primary-challenge Senator Roberts survives Tea Party challenge], foxnews.com; accessed October 21, 2015.</ref> He was a Kansas representative on the [[Republican National Committee]]. On November 18, 2016, he was selected by [[President-elect of the United States|President-elect]] [[Donald Trump]] to be Trump's nominee for [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref>{{cite press release|url=https://www.greatagain.gov/news/president-elect-donald-j-trump-selects-us-senator-jeff-sessions-attorney-general-lt-gen-michael.html|title=President-Elect Donald J. Trump Selects U.S. Senator Jeff Sessions for Attorney General, Lt. Gen. Michael Flynn as Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs and U.S. Rep. Mike Pompeo as Director of the Central Intelligence Agency|location=New York, New York|publisher=Office of the President Elect and of the Vice President Elect|accessdate=2016-11-18}}</ref>\n\n==Education, and early career==\nPompeo was born in [[Orange, California]], the son of Dorothy (n\u00e9e Mercer) and Wayne Pompeo.<ref name=\"TopHonor\">{{cite web | last1=Jarlson | first1=Gary | title=Santa Ana Cadet Wins Top West Point Honor | url=http://articles.latimes.com/1986-05-31/local/me-8260_1_west-point | date=May 31, 1986 | publisher=''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' | accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last1=Lee | first1=Teresa | title=Pompeo Visits Mother's Childhood Home | url=http://www.wellingtondailynews.com/article/20101020/NEWS/310209896 | date=October 20, 2010 | publisher=''[[The Wellington Daily News]]'' | accessdate=December 5, 2016}}</ref> He attended the [[United States Military Academy|U.S. Military Academy]] where he majored in [[Mechanical Engineering]], graduating first in his class in 1986 and subsequently serving in the Regular Army as an [[Armor Branch]] cavalry officer from 1986 to 1991.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://pompeo.house.gov|title=Congressman Mike Pompeo|accessdate=October 21, 2015}}</ref> He received his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] from [[Harvard Law School]], where he was an editor of the [[Harvard Law Review]]. He then worked as a lawyer for [[Williams & Connolly]].<ref>{{cite news|first=Dion|last=Lefler|title=Pompeo hopes varied background gives him edge|date=2010-07-29|url=http://www.kansas.com/2010/07/23/1415735/pompeo-hopes-varied-background.html|work=Wichita Eagle|accessdate=2010-08-04}}</ref>\n\n==Military service==\n{{BLP sources section|date=December 2016}}\nAs a teenager, he enrolled at the United States Military Academy at West Point. He graduated first in his class from West Point in 1986.<ref name=\"TopHonor\"/> According to his official biography, he then served as a cavalry officer patrolling the Iron Curtain before the fall of the Berlin Wall.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kelly|first1=Mary Louise|title=For CIA Nominee Mike Pompeo, 'Not A Good Situation To Inherit'|url=http://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2016/12/14/505512643/for-cia-nominee-mike-pompeo-not-a-good-situation-to-inherit|accessdate=29 December 2016|publisher=National Public Radio|date=December 14, 2016}}</ref> He also served with the 2nd Squadron, 7th Cavalry in the Fourth Infantry Division. He served his last tour in the [[Gulf War]].\n\n==Business career==\nPompeo founded Thayer Aerospace and Private Security.<ref>{{cite news|first=Benet|last=Wilson|title=Thayer Aerospace Founder Vies For Congress|date=2010-03-05 |url=http://www.aviationweek.com/aw/generic/story_generic.jsp?channel=busav&id=news/awx/2010/03/05/awx_03_05_2010_p0-209736.xml&headline=Thayer%20Aerospace%20Founder%20Vies%20For%20Congress|work=Aviation Week|accessdate=2010-08-04}}</ref> In 2006 he sold his interest in Thayer (which was renamed Nex-Tech Aerospace). He became the President of Sentry International, an oilfield equipment company.<ref>{{cite web|author1=Mike Pompeo|title=Congressman Mike Pompeo Biography|url=http://pompeo.house.gov/biography|publisher=house.gov|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==U.S. House of Representatives==\n\n===Elections===\n;2010\n{{Main|United States House of Representatives elections in Kansas, 2010#District 4}}\n\nIn the 2010 Kansas Republican primary for the 4th District Congressional seat, Pompeo defeated [[Kansas State Senate|State Senator]] [[Jean Schodorf]] (who received 24%), [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]] businessman Wink Hartman (who received 23%), and small business owner Jim Anderson (who received 13%). State Senator [[Dick Kelsey (politician)|Dick Kelsey]] also ran for the nomination, but ended his campaign before the August primary and endorsed Pompeo.<ref>{{cite news|first=Dion|last=Lefler|author2=Ron Sylvester|title=Pompeo, Goyle to Meet in 4th District race |date=2010-08-03 |url=http://www.kansas.com/2010/08/03/1431486/hard-fought-battle-nears-end-in.html|work=Wichita Eagle |accessdate=2010-08-04|quote=Republican National Committeeman Mike Pompeo survived a bruising GOP primary and Rep. Raj Goyle of Wichita steamrolled his Democratic opponent to set up the general election battle in the Kansas 4th Congressional District.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Tricia|last=Miller|title=Pompeo Likely To Replace Tiahrt|date=2010-08-04|url=http://blogs.cqpolitics.com/eyeon2010/2010/08/kansas-pompeo-hartman-schodorf.html |work=CQ Politics|accessdate=2010-08-04}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|first=Shane|last=D'Aprile|title=Pompeo wins GOP primary in Rep. Tiahrt's district |date=2010-08-04 |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/ballot-box/house-races/112553-pompeo-wins-gop-primary-in-rep-tiahrts-district |work=The Hill|accessdate=2010-08-04}}</ref> Late in the primary, Schodorf began to surge, prompting two outside groups\u2014Americans for Prosperity and Common Sense Issues, an Ohio-based political group\u2014to enter the race, spending tens of thousands of dollars in the final campaign days to attack Schodorf and support Pompeo.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kansas.com/2010/08/03/1431486/pompeo-goyle-4th-district.html|title=Pompeo, Goyle to meet in 4th District race|date=August 3, 2010|work=Wichita Eagle|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn the general election, Pompeo defeated [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee [[Kansas House of Representatives|State Representative]] [[Raj Goyle]]. Pompeo received 59% of the vote (117,171 votes), to 36% for Goyle (71,866).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/results/house|title=House Results Map|work=The New York Times|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the campaign, Pompeo received $80,000 in donations from [[Koch Industries]] and its employees.<ref name=\"Eggen\">{{cite news|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/pompeo-draws-liberal-groups-ire/2011/03/10/ABogK33_story.html|title=GOP freshman Pompeo turned to Koch for money for business, then politics|last=Eggen|first=Dan|date=March 20, 2011|newspaper=Washington Post|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n;2012\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Kansas, 2012#District 4}}\nIn his 2012 re-election bid, Pompeo defeated Democratic nominee Robert Tillman by a margin of 62%-32%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cjonline.com/news/2015-10-01/wichita-attorney-dan-giroux-announces-challenge-rep-mike-pompeo#|title=Wichita attorney Dan Giroux announces challenge to Rep. Mike Pompeo|accessdate=July 24, 2016}}</ref>\n\n;2014\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Kansas, 2014#District 4}}\nPompeo won the general election, defeating Democrat Perry Schuckman, with 66.7% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sos.ks.gov/elections/14elec/2014%20General%20Election%20Official%20Results.pdf|title=Kansas Secretary of State 2014 General Election|publisher=Kansas Secretary of State|date=November 4, 2014|accessdate=December 29, 2014}}</ref>\n\n;2016\n{{See also|United States House of Representatives elections in Kansas, 2016#District 4}}\nPompeo won the general election with 60.6% of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|title=Official Vote Totals|url=https://www.sos.ks.gov/elections/16elec/2016_General_Election_Official_Results.pdf|publisher=Kansas Secretary of State|page=2|accessdate=December 1, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Committee assignments===\nPompeo has been on the [[United States House Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence|Permanent Select Committee on Intelligence]] and [[United States House Committee on Energy and Commerce|Committee on Energy and Commerce]], and the following 3 subcommittees: the [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade|Subcommittee on Commerce, Manufacturing and Trade]], the [[United States House Energy Subcommittee on Energy and Power|Subcommittee on Energy and Power]], and the Subcommittee on the CIA. He is also on the [[House Select Committee on the Events Surrounding the 2012 Terrorist Attack in Benghazi]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Lowry|first=Bryan|url=http://www.kansas.com/news/politics-government/article1142515.html|title=Rep. Mike Pompeo appointed to Benghazi investigation committee|publisher=Kansas.com|date=2014-05-09|accessdate=2016-07-24}}</ref>\n\n==Nomination to be CIA Director==\nOn November 18, 2016, [[President-elect of the United States|President-elect]] [[Donald Trump]] announced that he would nominate Pompeo to be the [[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]].<ref>{{cite web|title=President-Elect Donald J. Trump Selects U.S. Senator Jeff Sessions for Attorney General, Lt. Gen. Michael Flynn as Assistant to the President for National Security Affairs and U.S. Rep. Mike Pompeo as Director of the Central Intelligence Agency|url=https://www.greatagain.gov/news/president-elect-donald-j-trump-selects-us-senator-jeff-sessions-attorney-general-lt-gen-michael.html|website=President Elect Donald J. Trump|accessdate=November 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Political positions==\n[[File:Mike Pompeo by Gage Skidmore 2.jpg|left|thumb|Pompeo speaking at the [[Values Voter Summit]] in Washington, D.C.]]\n\n===Abortion===\nPompeo is strongly opposed to [[Abortion in the United States|abortion]], except in cases when the mother's life is at risk.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://projects.wsj.com/campaign2012/candidates/view/mike-pompeo--KS-H|title=Election 2012: Mike Pompeo|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> He does not support abortion in cases of [[rape]] and [[incest]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://cjonline.com/news/2012-10-24/pompeo-no-rape-exception-anti-abortion-view|title=Pompeo: No rape exception in anti-abortion view|last=Hegeman|first=Roxana|date=October 24, 2012|newspaper=Topeka Capital-Journal|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Energy and environment===\nOn May 9, 2013, Pompeo introduced the [[Natural Gas Pipeline Permitting Reform Act (H.R. 1900; 113th Congress)]].<ref name=\"1900sum\">{{cite web|title=H.R. 1900 \u2013 Summary |url=http://beta.congress.gov/bill/113th/house-bill/1900|publisher=United States Congress|accessdate=November 21, 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe bill placed a 12-month deadline on the [[Federal Energy Regulatory Commission]], requiring it to approve or reject any proposal for a natural gas pipeline within that timeframe.<ref name=\"thursdaypipelines\">{{cite news|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|title=Thursday:Pipelines in the House, amendment fight in the Senate |url=http://thehill.com/blogs/floor-action/scheduling/191008-thursday-pipelines-in-the-house-amendment-fight-in-the-senate|accessdate=September 24, 2015|newspaper=The Hill|date=November 21, 2013}}</ref> The bill passed the House along party lines but not voted on in the Senate.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://politics.nytimes.com/congress/votes/113/house/1/611|title=Congressional Bills and Votes H.R. 1900|work=The New York Times}}</ref>\n\nPompeo rejects many concepts about global warming.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=http://www.c-spanvideo.org/clip/4456999|title=Mike Pompeo on Washington Journal|publisher=C-SPAN.org|accessdate=2016-11-18}}</ref> In 2013, he said, \"There are scientists who think lots of different things about climate change. There's some who think we're warming, there's some who think we\u2019re cooling, there's some who think that the last 16 years have shown a pretty stable climate environment.\"<ref name=\":0\"/>\n\nPompeo has referred to [[Barack Obama|President Obama]]'s environment and climate change plans as \"damaging\" and \"radical\".<ref name=\":1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.kansas.com/news/local/article47864260.html|title=Kansas starts working toward clean air plan that Pompeo wants to kill|newspaper=Wichita Eagle|accessdate=2016-11-18}}</ref> He opposes the regulation of [[Greenhouse gas emissions by the United States|greenhouse gas emissions]], and supports eliminating the [[Environmental Protection Agency]]'s greenhouse gas registry program.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://votesmart.org/candidate/political-courage-test/125023/mike-pompeo/#.U0WhjsdNpeE|title=Mike Pompeo's Issue Positions|publisher=Project Vote Smart|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> He has said that Obama's Clean Power Plan does not provide \"any measurable environmental benefit.\"<ref name=\":1\"/>\n\nHe signed the [[Americans for Prosperity]]'s No Climate Tax pledge.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.noclimatetax.com/pledge-signatories|title=Pledge Takers|publisher=[[Americans for Prosperity]]|work=NoClimateTax.com|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> He has called for the elimination of [[wind power]] production tax credits, calling them an \"enormous government handout\".<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kansas.com/2012/09/30/2507452/rep-mike-pompeo-wind-tax-credit.html|title=Rep. Mike Pompeo: Wind tax credit harms economy|last=Pompeo|first=Mike|date=September 30, 2012|newspaper=Wichita Eagle|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> He predicted a new energy bill would cost millions of jobs and make the United States a net food importer.<ref>[http://www.kansas.com/news/story/964455.html \"Pompeo predicts new energy bill would cost millions of jobs and make the United States a net food importer\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2016}}, kansas.com; accessed September 24, 2015.</ref>{{clarify|date=November 2016}}\n\n===Firearms===\nPompeo is a lifetime member of the [[National Rifle Association]], which has endorsed him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pompeoforcongress.com/media/?subsec=6&id=330|title=National Rifle Association Endorses Pompeo|work=Pompeo for Congress|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Healthcare===\nPompeo opposes the [[Affordable Care Act]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.usatoday.com/story/opinion/2013/05/10/affordable-care-act-obamacare-column/2144409|title=The ObamaCare train wreck: Column|last=Pompeo|first=Mike|date=September 3, 2013|newspaper=USA Today|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Genetically modified foods===\nPompeo opposes requiring food suppliers to label food made with [[genetically modified organisms]], and to that end in April 2014 introduced the \"Safe and Accurate Food Labeling Act\" to block states from requiring mandatory GMO food labeling.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.reuters.com/article/2014/04/09/usa-gmo-lawmaking-idUSL2N0N115F20140409|title=U.S. bill seeks to block mandatory GMO food labeling by states|last=Gillam|first=Carey|date=April 9, 2014|newspaper=Reuters|accessdate=May 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Government shutdown===\nPompeo supported the [[United States federal government shutdown of 2013|U.S. federal government shutdown of 2013]], blaming President Obama while acknowledging that the Republican Party could take a hit from the shutdown. He stated that he believed the shutdown was necessary to avoid a predicted \"American financial collapse 10 years from now.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kansas.com/2013/10/07/3045466/rep-pompeo-shutdown-is-about-substantial.html|title=Pompeo: For the GOP, shutdown is now about reforming entitlement programs|last=Wilson|first=Bill|date=October 2, 2013|newspaper=Wichita Eagle|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2014, Pompeo voted against a two-year budget deal drafted by [[Paul Ryan]] that would avert any government shutdown until 2015 and cut deficits by $23 billion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://projects.washingtonpost.com/congress/members/P000602/key-votes|title=Key Votes by Mike Pompeo \u2013 U.S. Congress Votes Database \u2013 The Washington Post}}</ref>\n\n===Manufacturing===\nPompeo introduced the [[Small Airplane Revitalization Act of 2013]] into the House on May 7, 2013.\n\n===Military===\nPompeo has been critical of President Obama, whom he repeatedly alleged was indecisive and not appropriately respectful of military leaders such as [[Stanley A. McChrystal|General McChrystal]], who was forced to submit his resignation for having made negative comments about the president to ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' magazine. He accused the president of \"unforgivably fail[ing] to provide the total commitment of our national means to our servicemen in the field.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.pompeoforcongress.com/media/index.cfm?subsec=6&id=97|title=Pompeo Responds to President's West Point Speech|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===National security===\n[[File:Mike Pompeo by Gage Skidmore.jpg|right|thumb|Pompeo speaking at the Conservative Political Action Conference (CPAC) in Washington, D.C.]]\nPompeo supports the [[National Security Agency]]'s surveillance programs, characterizing the agency's efforts as \"good and important work.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.kansas.com/2013/11/04/3097204/nsa-is-doing-important-work-pompeo.html|title=NSA is doing \u2018important work\u2019, Pompeo tells Wichita State students|last=Lefler|first=Dion|date=November 4, 2013|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> In March 2014, Pompeo denounced NSA whistleblower [[Edward Snowden]]'s inclusion in the [[South by Southwest]] conference in [[Austin, Texas]], and called for Snowden's invitation to speak via telecast at the annual Texas event be withdrawn, lest it encourage \"lawless behavior\" among attendees.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2014/03/sxsw-2014-edward-snowden-mike-pompeo-104462.html|title=SXSW 2014: Mike Pompeo wants Edward Snowden off the bill|last=Drusch|first=Andrea|date=March 9, 2014|newspaper=Politico|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> In February 2016, Pompeo said Snowden \"should be brought back from Russia and given due process, and I think the proper outcome would be that he would be given a death sentence.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.washingtonexaminer.com/lawmaker-traitor-snowden-deserves-death-penalty/article/2583023|title=Lawmaker: 'Traitor' Snowden deserves death penalty|newspaper=Washington Examiner|accessdate=2016-11-18}}</ref>\n\nPompeo has advocated for rolling back post-Snowden surveillance reforms, saying \"Congress should pass a law re-establishing collection of all metadata, and combining it with publicly available financial and lifestyle information into a comprehensive, searchable database. Legal and bureaucratic impediments to surveillance should be removed. That includes Presidential Policy Directive-28, which bestows privacy rights on foreigners and imposes burdensome requirements to justify data collection.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.wsj.com/articles/time-for-a-rigorous-national-debate-about-surveillance-1451856106|title=Time for a Rigorous National Debate About Surveillance|last=Jr|first=Mike Pompeo And David B. Rivkin|date=2016-01-03|newspaper=Wall Street Journal|issn=0099-9660|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref>\n\nOn July 21, 2015, Pompeo and Senator [[Tom Cotton]] alleged the existence of secret side agreements between Iran and the [[International Atomic Energy Agency|IAEA]] on procedures for inspection and verification of Iran's nuclear activities under the [[Joint Comprehensive Plan of Action|Iran nuclear deal]]. The Obama administration denied any clandestine or secret actions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.washingtonpost.com/news/powerpost/wp/2015/07/22/secret-deals-become-latest-congressional-complaint-about-iran-deal|title=\u2018Secret deals\u2019 become latest congressional complaint about Iran deal|author=Demirjian, Karoun}}</ref><ref name=IranSideDealCounterattack>{{cite web|url=http://thehill.com/policy/international/249171-white-house-launches-counterattack-against-iran-side-deal-attacks|title=White House launches Iran side deals counterattack|author=Jordan Fabian and Kristina Wong}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/entry/john-kerry-iran-deal-iaea_55b14997e4b08f57d5d41c12|title=John Kerry's Confident The IAEA Can Handle Iran, But Congress Isn't Buying It|author=Schulberg, Jessica|accessdate=September 24, 2015}}</ref>\n\nAdministration officials acknowledge the existence of agreements between Iran and the IAEA governing the inspection of sensitive military sites, but deny the characterization that they are \u201csecret side deals,\u201d saying instead that they are standard practice in crafting arms-control pacts and that the Administration had provided the information on them that was at its disposal to Congress.<ref name=IranSideDealCounterattack/>\n\nIn a 2013 speech on the House floor, Pompeo said Muslim leaders who fail to denounce acts of terrorism done in the name of Islam are \"potentially complicit\" in the attacks.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://thehill.com/video/house/304743-gop-lawmaker-silence-on-terror-attacks-makes-islamic-leaders-potentially-complicit|title=GOP lawmaker: US Muslim leaders 'complicit' in terrorist attacks|last=Kasperowicz|first=Pete|date=June 11, 2013|newspaper=The Hill|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref> The [[Council on American-Islamic Relations]] called on Pompeo to revise his remarks, calling them \"false and irresponsible\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cair.com/images/letters/Pompeo-letter.pdf|title=GOP lawmaker: US Muslim call Pompeo comments leaders \"false and irresponsible\"|publisher=Council on American-Islamic Relations|accessdate=April 9, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPompeo opposes closing [[Guant\u00e1namo Bay detention camp]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2013/jul/24/senate-debates-closing-guantanamo-bay|title=Senate debates Guant\u00e1namo in first hearing on closing prison since 2009|date=July 24, 2014|newspaper=Associated Press|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref> After a 2013 visit to the prison, Pompeo said, of the prisoners who were on hunger strike, \"It looked to me like a lot of them had put on weight.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.msnbc.com/msnbc/gop-rep-no-crisis-gitmo-detainees-hav|title=GOP Rep: \u2018No crisis\u2019 at Gitmo, detainees \u2018have put on weight\u2019|date=May 26, 2013|newspaper=MSNBC|accessdate=April 8, 2014}}</ref>\n\nPompeo has criticized the Obama administration's decision to end the CIA's secret prisons (so-called \"[[black site]]s\"), and the administration's requirement that all interrogators adhere to anti-torture laws.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2016/11/19/us/politics/donald-trump-administration.html|title=Trump Turns to His Right Flank to Fill National Security Posts|last=Davis|first=Julie Hirschfeld|date=2016-11-18|newspaper=The New York Times|issn=0362-4331|accessdate=2016-11-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Kansas/Government/Federal/US_House_of_Representatives/Mike_Pompeo_%5BR-4%5D}}\n* {{C-SPAN|michaelpompeo}}\n* [http://maplight.org/us-congress/legislator/1442-mike-pompeo Maplight Campaign Contributions]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|us-hs}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Todd Tiahrt]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[List of United States Representatives from Kansas|U.S. House of Representatives]]<br>from [[Kansas's 4th congressional district]]|years=2011\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n<!-- |-\n{{s-gov}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John O. Brennan|John Brennan]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Director of the Central Intelligence Agency]]<br>{{small|Nominee}}|years=Taking office 2017}}\n{{s-inc}} -->\n|-\n{{s-prec|usa}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steven Palazzo]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Seniority in the United States House of Representatives|United States Representatives by seniority]]|years=273rd}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jim Renacci]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n<!-- {{DCIA}} -->\n{{KS-FedRep}}\n{{USHouseCurrent}}\n{{KansasUSRepresentatives}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Pompeo, Mike}}\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:American Presbyterians]]\n[[Category:Businesspeople in aviation]]\n<!-- [[Category:Directors of the Central Intelligence Agency]] -->\n[[Category:Harvard Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Kansas lawyers]]\n[[Category:Kansas 